Kslg XXXVIII (1917), p. 89 in Schloß Friedenhof near Kronburg; Similar drawing in Berlin repr. Belvedere XII (1928), p. 20 [...]</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Bruegel & Tapestries. The early Adoration of the Magi (Brussels) in its main lines of composition based on the tapestry of the same subject in the series/scenes from the Cult of Christ in the Vatican (Eugène Müntz, Les tapisseries de Raphael au Vatican, Paris 1897, p. 37) woven in the workshop of Pieter van Aelst, Brussels, 1520-1531. The design is not by Raphael himself but school. (There is a large elephant in the tapestry, as well as camels). The Resurrection of this series is the direct model for P. Coecke's Resurrection (also noticed by Kronig). Motifs from the Massacre of the Innocents survives in Vermeyen's Turcs picture and in Bruegel's Massacre. The Christ of the Ascension echoed in the Christ of Bruegel's Resurrection. If the composition of the Adoration is reversed as it appeared in the cartoon the relation to Bruegel is even closer.</parts.title>
